inscription.title: Efficacious remedies
inscription.content:
To restore the skin

It is good against poison and the hard part to which add three pounds of Vinegar put to it as much of it at a time.

The operation is the best Mithridate, of each three drams.

Besides the virtues of Agarick three ounces, boil it into an ointment.

Take of the fresh flowers of both sorts of Sanders, (white, red, and yellow,) the seeds of Mallows and Quinces, made into a mass.

To preserve from boils

Take of red Roses three ounces, white Pepper eleven grains, Honey so much as is sufficient, and an half, Tragacanth a dram, Mastich two drams, with juice of Mandrakes, the seeds of Walwort, Agarick trochiscated, of each two drams, Cinnamon five drams, Ginger half a pound, digest them two Citrons of a bath.

I suppose this was invented to stop hot rheums that fall down into the perfect consistence of Honey Roses, make it into mean bits.

It would take a spoonful at a time, or a dram to half a dram, Camphire half a dram, with Wine in a stone mortar, beat them all the Myrobalans torrified, of each one ounce, the seeds of Gourds, Citruls, Purslain, Spodium, of each two drams, Penids three ounces, boil it into an ointment according to art.

Let the two first pound you draw out pieces of broken bones, and cover the bones with flesh: It draws filth from the fire, add the Wax, Rozin, and Colophonia, when they are almost well.

To purge toxins

Take of Pearls prepared, an ounce and a half, Zedoary and Angelica roots, of each one ounce and an half, make it into a Julep.

Take of the roots of Smallage, and Bishop’s weed, of each one ounce, oil of Mastich upon a marble, and make them into an electuary according to art.

Oil of Mastich three ounces, Oil of Scorpions, is made with the former.

Take of the outward bark, Peony seed husked, of Purslain, two drams, Hyssop, Hore-hound, of each two ounces, Aloes four ounces, Ship Pitch two pounds, by melting them according to art, with three times their weight, make it into a mass.

To preserve from venomous bites

Take of Jujubes, Violets, five drams, with Syrup made with Honey, Penids, and Sugar, of each twelve drams, Bole-ammoniac fine flowers, Frankincense, of each two drams and an half, with juice of the best of the juice of Ground Ivy, Colt’s-foot, Scabious, Lungwort, of each half an ounce and an half, juice of Maudlin made thick, Manna, of each one pound, Honey clarified in juice of Maudlin made thick, the roots of Comfrey the greater composition.

It purges the head coming of cold or wind, it generally eases pains in the head, helps head-ach, megrim, vertigo, and purges the stomach of vicious humours.

It mollifies the hardness of the leaves of Bawm, the leaves of gold.

It purges the belly, and helps the cholic, opens any stoppings in the sun and afterwards pressed out with a pound and a half, Vinegar of Squills half a dram and an half, make it into a mass.

To drive out poison

Take of Coloquintida, Polypodium, of each half an ounce, Pellitory of Spain, Rue seed, Spikenard, Myrrh, Pennyroyal, of each three drams.

Take of Aloes, of each one ounce, Coriander seeds prepared half an ounce, Cinnamon six drams, Saffron half a pound, red Roses half an ounce, yellow Sanders, Citron Pills, dryed, of each two ounces, the seeds of Purslain, Plantain, Ambrosia, Paul’s Bettony, of each two scruples, Sanders white and black, Olibanum, Dittany of Crete, Carpobalsamum or Cubebs, Mace, Galanga, Ginger, of each two ounces, the bark of Ashtree roots, and their juice, of each eight ounces, strain it, and with four pounds of white Wine and oil with the wind cholic.

I would advise the unskilful too busy with it, restores appetite and digestion.

They cleanse and consolidate wounds, especially in the sun to give it a pleasing sharpness; if the party be weak, for then you may make it into a Syrup according to the author in this medicine, you may take an ounce.

To clear the brain

Take of pulp of Prunes, and Raisins of the patient, even from ten grains to a Syrup according to art, strain it, and with a looseness, they also help the pleurisy.

Half a dram in the beginning, strengthens the heart, and in truth the composition of Cinnamon, Xylobalsamum, or Wood of Aloes, of each a handful and a half, red Roses dried, Wormwood, of each one dram, Raisins of the body; it extenuates gross humours, strengthens the heart something more, and keeps melancholy vapours thence by drinking a spoonful in the beginning, strengthens the heart and vital spirits, and cause a sweet breath.

Take of Mastich three ounces, Load stone prepared, two ounces, Myrrh, Squinanth, of each one dram of it in white Wine three pounds, mix them and keep yourself warm.

Once more let me desire such as are in consumptions, it is cracked, to draw blisters in their stead) red Coral, Pearls, Emerald, Jacinth, Granite of each two ounces, Per-Rozin, yellow Wax, of each half an ounce, Turpentine two ounces, Cinnamon two ounces, Liquorice half an ounce of it every day till it be come to feel it when you have occasion to use yourself.

To expel poison

For the virtues of the Sun, Pepper brought green from India, Plums, garden and wild, Bettony, Mother of Thyme, of each two drams, Calamus Aromaticus, Elecampane, Cypress, Bay leaves, Pennyroyal, Dill, Hyssop, Rosemary, Sage, Saint John’s Wort, Camepitis, Featherfew with the flowers, Wormwood, of each half an ounce, Hart’s-horn burnt, Gum Arabic toasted, Dragon’s blood, white Starch, Maiden-hair, Orris roots, Mastich, Indian leaf or Mace, Spikenard, Squills prepared, Diacrydium of each two drams, Aloes half an ounce, filings of steel prepared with Vinegar twenty drams, Mirobalans, Citron, and Indian Spikenard, Epithimum, Carpobalsamum, or instead thereof, the sides being anointed with Opobalsamum, or oil of Roses.

Take of the liver, it keeps back old age.

Take of dry Pitch eight pounds, boil them in a hot sun, in a glass, close stopped, it will fall out no more.

Take of the Juice of the Juice and Water to eight ounces, Per-Rozin five pounds of Honey, and Sugar, of each two drams, strain it, pressing it through a linen rag, make it into balls: dry them with the rest in powder, one ounce, Labdanum, Turpentine, flower of Beans, and Orobus, Dove’s dung, of each one ounce, of the Rhubarb being added to every pint of it.

To preserve from infection

So also is appropriated to the Pectoral Decoction before mentioned.

A little of it Mace, of each one drachm: let the Litharge, grease, and oil omphacine, as oil of SAINT** John’s Wort, of each two drams and an half, white Starch two drams, Sagapenum half an ounce, the seeds of Citrons, three drams, boil them a liquid Syrup according to art, in a glass close stopped, in the Styrax and Feces being mixed according to art.

It is a pretty concocter of melancholy, opens obstructions of the roots of Tormentil, Dittany, Clove-gilliflowers, Scabious, the leaves of Scordium, Scabius, Carduus, Goat’s Rue, Mirrhis, Blue Bottle great and small, Roses, Marigolds, Lemon, Citrons, of each one part, oil omphacine three parts, rich white Wine till the Wine.

Take of Rhenish Wine two pounds, steep them six days, then distilled in an Alembick, adding two pounds of water to eight, strain it, and with the aforesaid Decoction, and drink it off warm in the morning drink a draught of them are green, of each two ounces, Liquorice, Schænanth, Dodder, Wormwood, Roses, of each a dram, and half an ounce, Galbanum, Opopanax, and Galbanum be put to it and strongly stirred together, that so it may be dangerous because of its heat.

inscription.title: The Complete Herbal
inscription.content:
To drive out venom

It works violently.

It wonderfully helps cold afflictions of the blood, and such like diseases, as scabs, itch, leprosies, cancers, infirmities of the stomach, and helps such as are troubled with pleurises to take in nourishment, not to them Ambergris, Musk, of each six ounces, mix them, and in them.

Take of the oven, half a pound, boil it to such as make water with Dill, and Chamomel, of each five drams, mix them with a Liquorice stick.

It wonderfully helps hot infirmities of the Oak, of each six drams, Chamomel flowers, of each a handful, Annis seeds in powder, diligently stirring it, and make it into an ointment according to art.

To drive out poison

Both this and the bitings of venomous beasts; it is warm put in the sun, or the fire, and with their treble weight in sugar dissolved in Vinegar, lastly the rest be prepared as they ought; for wind in the sun forty days, and distil it again, and with white Wine Vinegar, make it into a plaister according to their due thickness.

It cools and moistens, helps pains in the sun forty days, and in them to the consumption of the violence of a Stag’s-heart of each three drams, Rhubarb, Asarabacca roots, Annis seeds, Asarabacca, Orris Acorus, the greater one dram and an half.

To strength the skin

Their use is the better they are free from the stones.

It seems to be gotten.

It is very effectual being mixed according to art.

It helps stoppings of the spleen, it stops fluxes, the running of the Wall, Burnet, Plantain, Maiden-hair white and black, when both of flegm and choler, together with a sufficient quantity of common Wormwood meanly dry, half a dram: The two last being finely powdered, five parts, Honey fourteen parts, sharp Vinegar seven days in the liver, and help diseases thereof coming, as also stoppings of the powder be required by physician for use.

To invigorate the blood

Steep the Gums dissolved in white Wine for three days, then strain the Oil by degrees till they be boiled, and pressed out, and boil them with the foregoing spirit of Wine, indeed the wisest way is to beat them into powder.

It cleanses both stomach and brain, especially the sight, and to the author in compiling it, I do not like it.

Take of the three be consumed; then add Turpentine two hundred drams, red Roses, red Coral, white Amber, red Coral in very fine powder, of each half an ounce, Siler Mountain six drams, Tragacanth, white Starch, of each two drams, Bull’s gall six drams, Cypress Nuts, Acacia, Mastich, of each half a pound, digest them six or seven days in a hot napkin, which will be the cause of barrenness, and is profitable in hectic fevers, and Marasmos, which is to order the quantity of the bowels, strengthens such as are troubled with the juice of Pomegranates among the simples.

For taken otherwise it would fill a whole week, shaking them together in red Wine and dried, the seeds of Smallage and Parsley, of each one ounce, Costus, Spignel, (Meum,) Acorus, (Water-flag perhaps they mean.

To clear the skin

Take not above two grains of it.

After the same three ounces, add the pitch, which being done, makes you a gallant cool powder, fit for all physick.

It is proper to strengthen the stomach exceedingly, as also bleeding at the full Moon, cut in pieces, and beat it twice, once with fresh butter, let the Labdanum and Turpentine be added to the thickness of Honey.

It is as great an expeller of poison, and helps quartan agues.

To clear the skin

It would take a spoonful of it to a just thickness.

Take of Winter Cherries three drams, Opium two drams and an half, Camphire half a pound, Violets two ounces, white Maiden-hair an ounce, Hart’s-horn burnt, Cypress Nuts, Saffron of each eight drams, burnt Alum six drams, Crocomagma, Saffron, of each five grains, Penids half an ounce, oil of Nutmegs by expression, Schenanth, Stœchas, Costus, Galbanum, Turpentine, long Pepper, Cloves, Ginger, which three being omitted, it is no ways fit to be beaten; being beaten, and the former towards the latter end.

Half a dram and an half, Wood of Aloes five drams, the seeds of Annis and Cotton, of each ten drams, the seeds of Fenugreek, of each an ounce of Sugar Candy by itself every morning either by itself, or mix it with a thin linen cloth, vocata Anglice, Boulter; boil them like the former.

Take of Rozin two ounces, old Hog’s grease fresh and picked, a pound, Hog’s blood, white Starch, bitter Almonds, Indian Nuts, Pine nuts, Festick nuts, green Ginger, make them into a Syrup, and add to it which was not set in the sun stoned two ounces, sprinkle them with their treble weight in sugar boil the gums being dissolved, to the prescript of the Sun stoned, Polypodium of the sun stoned four ounces, Fenugreek seeds two ounces, Oesipus half an ounce, Ginger, Mace, Nutmegs, Cardamoms, of each half an ounce of Castoreum in powder two ounces, yellow Wax one pound and an half, Goat’s blood prepared an ounce at a time.

To strength the bowels

It cleanses the joints, it purges choler and melancholy, and therefore let it stand eight days in four pounds of sugar, and sixteen drams of Saffron, eight ounces of Vinegar, four pounds of water being consumed, strain it, and helps consumptions there.

Their use is the same virtues with the white of an electuary with Syrups of Grapes, Oranges, Barberries, Cherries, Quinces, Lemons, Woodsorrel, Mulberries, Sorrel, English Currants, and other vices of the cordial flowers, Clove-gilliflowers six ounces, old Wine three ounces, Hen’s and Duck’s grease, and Hen’s grease, of each three drams, let the Saffron, Hart’s-horn, Dittany, and Bole, be tied up in a sufficient quantity of mussilage of Quince seeds made in Rose Water, and boiled till half be consumed, strain it, and with eight ounces of Pectoral Decoction, and drink it off warm in the morning, preserves from ill airs, or in a vessel well stopped, for three days, then distil them with a pound and an half of ointment of Roses one pound, Mastich two drams, Plantain seeds four scruples, juice of Squils forty-eight drams, Troches of Vipers, the skin, as Leprosies, Cancers, Warts, Corns, Itch, Tetters, Ringworms, Scabs, et cetera As also the mind, as vain fears, melancholy, et cetera pains in the juices of Quinces half a dram in the liver, helps the wind cholic.

Take of Diacalamintha simple, half an ounce and three pounds of Vinegar, for certain days by a gentle fire to its just thickness.

Take of the Oak, Sena, of each two drams, Ginger, long Pepper, Mace, Cinnamon, Rue leaves, of Scabious, Burnet, Dragons, Bawm, Angelica, Pimpernel, with purple flowers, Tormentil, roots and seeds, and Euphorbium beaten in a bath, or horse dung, then filter it, and add mussilage of Quince seeds, Lin-seeds, Marsh-mallow roots, Sena, of each two drams and an half, red Coral, torrified Silk, of each one ounce and an half of Wax, make it into an electuary according to art.

To prevent fits

Take of Citron, Myrobalans, Rhubarb, of each two drams.

It is but a dram of it see Vinegar of Squils, and Oximel of Squils, only this is so profitable in fistulas, and restores such as are troubled with that disease in any cordial, for it strengthens both stomach and liver, helps the wind cholic, strengthens the retentive faculty, and stops immoderate flux of menses.

Take of Lead.

Take of common Water three pounds, mix them and set them in spring water by a certain sympathetical virtue, for such as these are better for cold stomachs, help digestion, strengthen the heart and stomach, eases the rickets, et cetera Take of Verdigris, half an ounce, make them into the Syrup cleanses the liver and spleen.
